	<h2>Permit and Inspection Considerations</h2>

	<h3>Professional Permit Handling</h3>
	<p>What contractors provide:</p>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>Application preparation:</strong> Complete and accurate permit applications</li>
		<li><strong>Code knowledge:</strong> Build to code requirements first time</li>
		<li><strong>Inspection scheduling:</strong> Contractor coordinates all inspections</li>
		<li><strong>Correction handling:</strong> Fix any inspection issues at no additional charge</li>
		<li><strong>Final approval:</strong> Ensure project passes final inspection</li>
		<li><strong>Your involvement:</strong> Minimal - just approve design and final result</li>
	</ul>

	<h3>DIY Permit Challenges</h3>
	<p>Homeowner permit process reality:</p>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>Learning curve:</strong> Understanding permit requirements and process</li>
		<li><strong>Application errors:</strong> Common for first-time applicants</li>
		<li><strong>Code compliance:</strong> Must research and understand all applicable codes</li>
		<li><strong>Inspection scheduling:</strong> You coordinate timing, be available for inspector</li>
		<li><strong>Failed inspections:</strong> Common first-time DIY issue, requires corrections</li>
		<li><strong>Time investment:</strong> 4-8 hours total for permit process</li>
		<li><strong>Correction costs:</strong> $200-800 if significant changes required after failed inspection</li>
	</ul>

	<h2>Physical Demands and Safety</h2>

	<h3>Physical Requirements</h3>
	<p>Realistic assessment of physical demands:</p>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>Heavy lifting:</strong> 60-80 lb bags of concrete, 16-foot boards, posts</li>
		<li><strong>Repetitive stress:</strong> Hundreds of screws to drive, boards to lift</li>
		<li><strong>Extended standing/kneeling:</strong> 6-8 hours per day on project</li>
		<li><strong>Upper body strength:</strong> Operating power auger, lifting materials overhead</li>
		<li><strong>Heat tolerance:</strong> Working in Stockton summer heat (95-105°F)</li>
		<li><strong>Endurance:</strong> Multi-day project requiring sustained effort</li>
	</ul>

	<h3>Common DIY Injuries</h3>
	<p>Safety risks and prevention:</p>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>Hand blisters:</strong> Near-universal DIY fence experience, quality gloves essential</li>
		<li><strong>Back strain:</strong> Lifting heavy materials improperly, take breaks</li>
		<li><strong>Power tool injuries:</strong> Saw cuts, drill injuries - follow all safety protocols</li>
		<li><strong>Heat exhaustion:</strong> Working in Central Valley summer heat - hydrate, take breaks</li>
		<li><strong>Struck by objects:</strong> Dropped boards, swinging gates - stay alert</li>
		<li><strong>Eye injuries:</strong> Flying debris from cutting - always wear safety glasses</li>
	</ul>

	<h2>Decision Framework: DIY vs. Professional</h2>

	<h3>DIY Makes Sense When:</h3>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>You have significant construction experience</strong> - Not first major project</li>
		<li><strong>You own necessary tools</strong> - Tool investment under $200</li>
		<li><strong>You have help available</strong> - Friend or family with experience assisting</li>
		<li><strong>Timeline is flexible</strong> - No deadline pressure, can work at your pace</li>
		<li><strong>Project is small/simple</strong> - Under 75 linear feet, flat yard, no obstacles</li>
		<li><strong>Budget is very tight</strong> - Can't afford professional installation currently</li>
